04732nam a22008535i 9780823245550DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232455507 a10.1515/97808232455502doi  a(DE-B1597)555121  a(OCoLC)960750981  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS217.E47bR58 2013eb 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a810.9/3532231 aRitzenberg, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sentimental Touch :bThe Language of Feeling in the Age of Managerialism /cAaron Ritzenberg. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Touching the Body, Training the Reader -- t2. Managing Sentimentalism in Adventures of Huckleberry Finn -- t3. Holding On to the Sentimental in Winesburg, Ohio -- t4. A Touch of Miss Lonelyhearts -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1850 and 1940, with the rise of managerial capitalism in the United States, the most powerful businesses ceased to be family owned, instead becoming sprawling organizations controlled by complex bureaucracies. Sentimental literature—work written specifically to convey and inspire deep feeling—does not seem to fit with a swiftly bureaucratizing society. Surprisingly, though, sentimental language persisted in American literature, even as a culture of managed systems threatened to obscure the power of individual affect.The Sentimental Touch explores the strange, enduring power of sentimental language in the face of a rapidly changing culture. Analyzing novels by Harriet Beecher Stowe, Mark Twain, Sherwood Anderson, and Nathanael West, the book demonstrates that sentimental language changes but remains powerful, even in works by authors who self-consciously write against the sentimental tradition. Sentimental language has an afterlife, enduring in American literature long after authors and critics declared it dead, insisting that human feeling can resist a mechanizing culture and embodying, paradoxically, the way that literary conventions themselves become mechanical and systematic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEmotions in literature. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aBody in literature.  aBusiness and literature.  aCapitalism and feeling.  aEmotion in literature.  aFeeling in literature.  aManagerialism.  aModernism.  aRealism.  aSentimentalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082324552940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823245550?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823245550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823245550/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK